[FEN "3k4/7R/p2P4/2p1b3/8/2P3rB/P4r2/1K2R3 w - - 3 41"]
[SetUp "1"]
[UTCDate "2019.06.03"]
[UTCTime "18:10:17"]
[ChapterMode "gamebook"]

{ This Lichess lesson is about setting up a Discovery. This is similar to setting up a pin, skewer, fork or other tactic.

How does White set up a Discovery? }
41. Rd7+ { Correct. Black should not play ...Ke8?? because then 42.Rxe5+. } (41. Rxe5?? { This is a blunder because now Black can force mate with ...Rg1+! } 41... Rg1+ 42. Bf1 Rgxf1+ 43. Re1 Rxe1#) (41. Be6? { This looks strong because it threatens, say, 41.Ra7 and then 42.Ra8#. However, Black has a good response in ...Bg7. } 41... Bg7 { Black has counter-play. }) (41. Rh8+?? { This loses the Rook to ...Bxh8. } 41... Bxh8 $19) (41. Rc7?? { This loses the Bishop to Rxh3. White cannot then play Rxe5 because his back rank is weak! } 41... Rxh3 $19 42. Rxe5?? Rh1+ 43. Re1 Rxe1#) 41... Kc8 { Since ...Ke8 would just lose the Bishop with check. } (41... Ke8 42. Rxe5+ $18 { White wins. }) 42. Rf7+ { Good. This is a clean win of the exchange and White gets a winning position. } (42. Rxe5?? { This is a blunder because now Black can force mate with ...Rg1+! } 42... Rg1+ 43. Bf1 Rgxf1+ 44. Re1 Rxe1#) (42. Rc7+ { This wins but is more complex than the main line. } 42... Kb8 43. Rc8+ Kb7 44. d7 Bf6 45. Bf1 Rd2 46. Re6 Rxd7 47. Bxa6+ Ka7 48. Rxf6 $18) (42. Rh7+ { This wins but is more complex than the main line. } 42... Kb8 43. d7 Bc7 44. Rh8+ Ka7 45. Rd1 Rf6 46. d8=Q Bxd8 47. Rdxd8 Rxc3 48. Ra8+ $18) 42... Rxh3 { Black has nothing better. } 43. Rxf2 { White has won the exchange. } (43. Rxe5?? { This is a blunder because now Black forces mate with ...Rh1+! } 43... Rh1+ 44. Re1 Rxe1#) 43... Bxd6 { Black gets his Bishop out of trouble and captures White's passed pawn. Is this going to be a difficult ending?
Find the move that makes the win easiest. } (43... Bg3 { This skewer does not work. } 44. Rf8+ Kd7 45. Rd1 $18) 44. Rf7 { Excellent! The threat is Re8#. Black will lose more material because his Bishop and pawns are loose and White will have mating threats.
- Did you notice White's back rank weakness in the initial position?
- Did you notice Black's unguarded pieces in the initial position?
- Are you uncomfortable with your ability to win the final position? If so analyze it with a computer to see the winning techniques. } 44... Kd8 *


