{ This is Discovered Check #5 in the Lichess practice. We are challenged to get a winning position in 3 moves. }
51. Qe8+ { Correct. White forces the removal of the blockade. } 51... Rxe8 { Black must take the Queen or else lose his Rook. There is no perpetual check draw because White's Queen would be able to interpose at h4. } (51... Kg7 52. Qxd8 Qd2+ 53. Kh3 Qh6+ 54. Qh4 $18) 52. d8=Q+ { Excellent. } (52. dxe8=Q+?? { This is a blunder because Black can respond ...Kxe8. } 52... Kxe8 $19) 52... Qe7 { Black was in check and his Queen was unguarded. Perhaps in a game ...Re7 and hope the opponent does not take the Queen! } (52... Re7 { Hoping for a blunder. } 53. Qxd6 Rxb7 54. Qd5+ $18 { The fork finishes Black. }) 53. Rxe7+ { Correct. Black will play ...Rxe7 and White can respond Qxb6 creating a passed pawn.
- Are you familiar with the pattern of removing the blockade on a passed pawn?
- Did you see that Black's Queen was unguarded?
Play the final position out with a computer for additional practice in winning a won game. } (53. Qxb6 { This also wins. }) (53. Qd5+ { This wins but White has a better move. }) (53. Qxe7+ { This is a blunder that loses the Queen to ...Rxe7. White has a much better move. }) (53. Qxe8+ { This is a blunder that loses the Queen to ...Kxe8. White has a much better move. }) *



